Formalities — s.9 Wills Act 1837.answer:
Under s.9 Wills Act 1837 (as amended by Administration of Justice Act 1982), a valid will must:

1. Be in writing;
2. Be signed by the testator (or by some other person in the testator's presence and by the testator's direction);
3. The testator must intend by their signature to give effect to the will;
4. The signature must be made or acknowledged in the presence of two or more witnesses present at the same time;
5. Each witness must attest and sign the will (or acknowledge their signature) in the presence of the testator.

Witnesses do not need to sign in each other's presence — only in the presence of the testator.

Revocation, alteration and revival.answer:
A will may be revoked by:

1. Marriage or civil partnership — s.18 Wills Act 1837: marriage automatically revokes an existing will unless the will was made in contemplation of that marriage (s.18(3));
2. A later valid will or codicil containing an express revocation clause, or inconsistent with the earlier will (implied revocation);
3. A written declaration of revocation executed with the same formalities as a will (s.20 Wills Act 1837);
4. Physical destruction — burning, tearing, or otherwise destroying the will by the testator (or by another in their presence and direction) with the intention to revoke it: s.20 Wills Act 1837.

Divorce or dissolution does not revoke a will but treats gifts to the former spouse and appointments of them as executor as lapsed: s.18A Wills Act 1837.

Further relatives and no relatives.answer:
Under s.46 AEA 1925, where there is no surviving spouse/civil partner or issue, the estate passes in the following order (the first category in which a relative survives takes the whole estate):

1. Parents (equally if both survive);
2. Siblings of the whole blood (or their issue per stirpes);
3. Siblings of the half blood (or their issue per stirpes);
4. Grandparents (equally if more than one);
5. Uncles and aunts of the whole blood (or their issue per stirpes);
6. Uncles and aunts of the half blood (or their issue per stirpes);
7. The Crown (bona vacantia).

Half-blood relatives are only entitled when there are no whole-blood relatives at the same degree.

Ademption and abatement.answer:
Abatement occurs where the estate is insufficient to satisfy all the testamentary gifts in full. Gifts are reduced (abated) proportionally within each category.

Order of abatement (gifts abate in this order — later categories are sacrificed first):
1. Residuary gifts — abate first and in full;
2. General gifts — abate rateably among themselves;
3. Demonstrative gifts — abate rateably;
4. Specific gifts — abate last.

All debts and funeral/testamentary expenses must be paid first before any gift is distributed. If the estate is insolvent, the statutory order for payment of debts applies (s.34 and Sch.1 AEA 1925).

